## PART 4 — TYPESCRIPT/REACT COMMENTING STANDARDS

### 4.1 Module-Level Comments

Add a module comment only when the file purpose is not fully captured by its name.
Most files do not need one.

```ts
/**
 * SSE invalidation bridge between the server-sent event stream and the
 * React Query cache. Subscribes to task change events and invalidates
 * the relevant query keys so components refetch automatically.
 *
 * Important: invalidation is intentionally coarse-grained (invalidates the
 * full task list) to avoid stale reads from partial cache updates. This
 * trades a small amount of over-fetching for correctness.
 */
```

### 4.2 Exported Functions and Hooks

Public functions and hooks get a JSDoc comment when the name alone does not
convey the full contract.

```ts
/**
 * Parses a raw API response into a typed Task. Throws if required fields
 * are absent or of the wrong type — this is intentional. A malformed
 * response indicates a contract violation between client and server that
 * should surface immediately rather than propagate as undefined behaviour.
 */
export function parseTask(raw: unknown): Task { ... }

/**
 * Subscribes to the task SSE stream and invalidates React Query cache
 * on change events. Safe to mount multiple times — deduplication is
 * handled by the SSE hub on the server side.
 *
 * Cleans up the EventSource connection on unmount. Do not call .close()
 * manually on the returned source — the hook owns its lifecycle.
 */
export function useTaskSSE(): void { ... }
```

### 4.3 Inline Comments

Same principle as Go: explain why, not what.

Non-obvious React behaviour:

```tsx
// useLayoutEffect rather than useEffect because we need the DOM measurement
// to happen synchronously before the browser paints. useEffect would cause
// a one-frame flicker as the tooltip repositions after initial render.
useLayoutEffect(() => {
    const rect = ref.current?.getBoundingClientRect();
    setPosition(calculatePosition(rect, viewport));
}, [viewport]);
```

Intentional dependency omissions:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
    subscribe(taskId);
    return () => unsubscribe(taskId);
// eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps
// Intentionally omitting subscribe and unsubscribe — they are stable
// module-level functions, not closures. Including them would re-run this
// effect on every render due to a limitation in the lint rule's static analysis.
}, [taskId]);
```

Non-obvious state decisions:

```ts
// Store the previous value in a ref rather than state so that updating it
// does not trigger a re-render. This value is only needed for comparison
// on the next render cycle, not for driving the UI.
const prevTaskId = useRef(taskId);
```

Subtle ordering or timing:

```ts
// Cancel the in-flight request before starting the new one. Without this,
// a slow previous request can resolve after the new one and overwrite
// the correct data with stale results.
abortControllerRef.current?.abort();
abortControllerRef.current = new AbortController();
```

Edge case protection:

```ts
// Empty string is a valid task title during optimistic creation before
// the server assigns a real value. Guard against rendering an empty
// string as falsy, which would show the fallback title incorrectly.
const displayTitle = task.title !== undefined ? task.title : 'Untitled';
```

Non-obvious type decisions:

```ts
// Cast is safe: the server guarantees status is one of the TaskStatus
// enum values. parseTask() validates this at the boundary. The cast here
// avoids re-validating in hot render paths.
const status = raw.status as TaskStatus;
```

### 4.4 CSS Comments

Comment only non-obvious rules. Layout tricks, magic numbers, and
browser-specific workarounds always need a comment.

```css
.task-card {
  /* Promotes to its own compositor layer, preventing the shimmer animation
     on skeleton children from triggering layout in the parent. Without this,
     animating opacity on a child forces a repaint of the whole card list. */
  will-change: transform;

  /* 52px = 44px touch target (Apple HIG minimum) + 4px top and bottom
     padding. Do not reduce below 52px on mobile breakpoints. */
  min-height: 52px;
}

.dropdown {
  /* z-index 200 places this above cards (z: 1) and modals (z: 100) but
     below the command palette (z: 300). See docs/DESIGN.md z-index scale
     for the full layer map. */
  z-index: 200;
}
```

Magic numbers always get a comment:

```css
/* BAD */
margin-top: 13px;

/* GOOD */
/* 13px = line-height (20px) - cap-height (7px). Optically aligns the
   label baseline with the adjacent icon centre. */
margin-top: 13px;
```

### 4.5 What Never Gets a Comment in TypeScript

```ts
const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);

if (!task) return null;

const tasks = data?.tasks ?? [];

router.push(`/tasks/${id}`);

export default TaskCard;
```

