## PART 5 — SQL COMMENTING STANDARDS

### 5.1 Migration Files

Each migration file gets a header comment explaining what it does and why.

```sql
-- Migration: 003_add_task_events_index.up.sql
--
-- Adds a composite index on (task_id, created_at) for task_events.
-- Without this index, the event history query for a task with many events
-- performs a full table scan. At ~10k events/day this became measurable
-- at p95 after load testing (see issue #89).
--
-- The index is partial (WHERE task_id IS NOT NULL) to exclude the small
-- number of system-level events that have no associated task.

CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_task_events_task_id_created_at
    ON task_events (task_id, created_at DESC)
    WHERE task_id IS NOT NULL;
```

### 5.2 Complex Queries

Non-trivial queries in Go store files get a comment explaining the intent,
especially when joins, CTEs, or window functions are involved.

```go
// selectLatestPhasePerCycle uses a lateral join rather than a subquery
// because the planner produces a significantly better plan when the
// outer query is already filtered by cycle_id. A correlated subquery
// here caused a sequential scan on task_cycle_phases in testing.
const q = `
    SELECT cp.*
    FROM task_cycles c
    CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
        SELECT * FROM task_cycle_phases
        WHERE cycle_id = c.id
        ORDER BY seq DESC
        LIMIT 1
    ) cp
    WHERE c.task_id = $1
`
```

