## PART 6 — GOOD VS BAD EXAMPLES

### Error handling

```go
// BAD — explains what, not why
// Check if error is not found
if errors.Is(err, domain.ErrNotFound) {
    return http.StatusNotFound
}

// GOOD — no comment needed, code is self-explanatory
if errors.Is(err, domain.ErrNotFound) {
    return http.StatusNotFound
}

// GOOD — comment only when the mapping is non-obvious
// ErrInvalidInput covers both missing required fields and illegal state
// transitions. Both surface to the client as 400 with the error detail
// in the body — the distinction is in the message, not the status code.
if errors.Is(err, domain.ErrInvalidInput) {
    respondError(w, http.StatusBadRequest, err.Error())
    return
}
```

### Concurrency

```go
// BAD — describes the code, not the reason
// Lock the mutex
s.mu.Lock()
defer s.mu.Unlock()

// GOOD — explains the invariant being protected
// Both the subscriber map and the closed flag must be read atomically.
// A subscriber added after close() would never receive the close signal
// and would leak. The write lock here ensures close() and Subscribe()
// are mutually exclusive.
s.mu.Lock()
defer s.mu.Unlock()
```

### React hook

```tsx
// BAD — restates the code
// Reset the form when taskId changes
useEffect(() => {
    reset();
}, [taskId, reset]);

// GOOD — no comment needed, intent is clear from the code

// GOOD — comment only when the behaviour is surprising
// Reset fires on mount (taskId going from undefined to string) which is
// intentional — it clears any state left from a previously edited task.
// This avoids a flash of stale data when navigating between tasks.
useEffect(() => {
    reset();
}, [taskId, reset]);
```

### A necessary warning

```go
// WARNING: do not add a cache here without also invalidating on task
// deletion. A previous attempt (removed in commit a3f9d2) caused deleted
// tasks to remain visible to users for up to 60 seconds. The performance
// gain was not worth the correctness risk at current scale.
func (s *PostgresTaskStore) GetByID(ctx context.Context, id uuid.UUID) (*Task, error) {
```

