## PART 7 — COMMENT MAINTENANCE RULES

Comments rot faster than code. A wrong comment is worse than no comment.

- Update comments in the same commit as the code they describe. A PR that
  changes logic without updating the relevant comment is incomplete.
- Delete comments when the condition they describe is resolved. A FIXME that
  no longer applies is misinformation.
- Never leave commented-out code in a commit. Git is the history.
- If you cannot update a comment because you do not understand it, surface it
  in review. Do not leave it and hope.

---

## PART 8 — DO NOT

- Do not write "increment counter" above count++
- Do not use comments to apologise for bad code — fix the code
- Do not write section dividers in files short enough to navigate without them
- Do not comment every struct field unless the name is genuinely ambiguous
- Do not write comments in a different language than the rest of the codebase
- Do not disable linter warnings without explaining why the warning is a false positive
- Do not leave TODO comments without an owner and a resolution condition
- Do not write commented-out code — delete it, git has the history

---

## PART 9 — QUICK REFERENCE

SITUATION                                        COMMENT?
Standard CRUD handler                            No
Error mapping domain to HTTP status              No
Non-obvious error mapping with edge case         Yes — explain the edge
Mutex lock in a simple setter                    No
Mutex protecting multiple fields atomically      Yes — explain what is protected and why
useEffect with obvious deps                      No
useEffect with intentionally omitted dep         Yes — explain why plus eslint-disable
Standard React Query hook                        No
SSE cleanup with subtle ordering                 Yes — explain the order dependency
Simple DB query                                  No
CTE or lateral join chosen for plan reasons      Yes — explain the query plan decision
Magic number (z-index, pixel offset)             Yes — always explain magic numbers
Token from the design system                     No
Migration that adds an index                     Yes — explain why the index is needed
Exported function with obvious signature         Godoc only if contract is non-trivial
Exported function with non-obvious contract      Godoc always
Unexported function with obvious purpose         No
Unexported function with non-obvious logic       Yes — explain the why